🧠 OS Concept 2: User Mode vs Kernel Mode
1️⃣ Simple Idea

CPU works in 2 modes:

User Mode   → restricted
Kernel Mode → full access
🧠 Real-World Analogy

🏫 College:

Students → limited access
Principal → full control
⚙️ Why It Exists

To protect system from:

malicious programs
accidental damage
⚙️ How It Works

1️⃣ Program runs in user mode
2️⃣ Needs OS → makes system call
3️⃣ Switch to kernel mode
4️⃣ OS does work
5️⃣ Back to user mode

🔗 Connection to System Calls

System calls trigger:

👉 mode switch

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why do we need dual mode operation?

👉 To ensure security and controlled access to hardware.

🧠 Memory Trick
User = Limited
Kernel = King 👑
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Instruction Pipeline Hazards

(Continuation of pipelining Day 4)

1️⃣ Simple Idea

Hazards =
👉 problems that stop smooth pipelining

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Assembly line stops because:

missing part
wrong order
machine conflict
⚙️ Types of Hazards
1️⃣ Data Hazard

Instruction depends on previous result

I1: A = B + C
I2: D = A + E

👉 I2 must wait

2️⃣ Control Hazard

Branch instruction

if (x > 0)

CPU doesn’t know next instruction

3️⃣ Structural Hazard

Hardware conflict

👉 two instructions need same resource

🔗 Connection to Pipelining

Hazards reduce:

👉 performance

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What are pipeline hazards?

👉 Data, Control, Structural hazards

🧠 Memory Trick
DCS → Data, Control, Structural
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Cache Mapping Techniques

🔥 Frequently asked

1️⃣ Simple Idea

Cache mapping =
👉 how memory blocks are placed in cache

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Parking system 🅿️

How cars are assigned slots

⚙️ Types
1️⃣ Direct Mapping

👉 One memory block → one cache line

✔ Simple
❌ conflict possible

2️⃣ Fully Associative

👉 Block can go anywhere

✔ Flexible
❌ expensive

3️⃣ Set Associative 🔥

👉 Combination of both

✔ balanced approach
✔ used in real systems

🔗 Connection to Cache (Day 5)

Mapping decides:

👉 cache performance

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Which cache mapping is best?

👉 Set associative (balance of speed & flexibility)

🧠 Memory Trick
Direct = fixed
Associative = anywhere
Set = hybrid
